# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: image-based-lighting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] The same cube mapping as above rendered as a 3D view.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] In computer graphics, **cube mapping** is a method of environment mapping that uses the six faces of a cube as the map shape.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] The environment is projected onto the sides of a cube and stored as six square textures, or unfolded into six regions of a single texture.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] The cube map is generated by first rendering the scene six times from a viewpoint, with the views defined by a 90 degree view frustum representing each cube face.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Or if the environment is first considered to be projected onto a sphere, then each face of the cube is its gnomonic projection.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] In the majority of cases, cube mapping is preferred over the older method of sphere mapping because it eliminates many of the problems that are inherent in sphere mapping such as image distortion, viewpoint dependency, and computational inefficiency.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Also, cube mapping provides a much larger capacity to support real-time rendering of reflections relative to sphere mapping because the combination of inefficiency and viewpoint dependency severely limits the ability of sphere mapping to be applied when there is a consistently changing viewpoint.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Variants of cube mapping are also commonly used in 360 video projection.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Cube mapping was first proposed in 1986 by Ned Greene in his paper "Environment Mapping and Other Applications of World Projections", ten years after environment mapping was first put forward by Jim Blinn and Martin Newell.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] However, hardware limitations on the ability to access six texture images simultaneously made it infeasible to implement cube mapping without further technological developments.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] This problem was remedied in 1999 with the release of the Nvidia GeForce 256.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Nvidia touted cube mapping in hardware as "a breakthrough image quality feature of GeForce 256 that ... will allow developers to create accurate, real-time reflections.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Cube mapping is preferred over other methods of environment mapping because of its relative simplicity.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Cube mapping also produces results that are similar to those obtained by ray tracing, but is much more computationally efficient – the moderate reduction in quality is compensated for by large gains in efficiency.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Pre-dating cube mapping, sphere mapping has many inherent flaws that made it impractical for most applications.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Sphere mapping is view-dependent, meaning that a different texture is necessary for each viewpoint.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Therefore, in applications where the viewpoint is mobile, it would be necessary to dynamically generate a new sphere mapping for each new viewpoint (or, to pre-generate a mapping for every viewpoint).
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Also, a texture mapped onto a sphere's surface must be stretched and compressed, and warping and distortion (particularly along the edge of the sphere) are a direct consequence of this.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Although these image flaws can be reduced using certain tricks and techniques like "pre-stretching", this just adds another layer of complexity to sphere mapping.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Paraboloid mapping provides some improvement on the limitations of sphere mapping, however it requires two rendering passes in addition to special image warping operations and more involved computation.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Conversely, cube mapping requires only a single render pass, and due to its simple nature, is very easy for developers to comprehend and generate.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Also, cube mapping uses the entire resolution of the texture image, compared to sphere and paraboloid mappings, which also allows it to use lower resolution images to achieve the same quality.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Although handling the seams of the cube map is a problem, algorithms have been developed to handle seam behavior and result in a seamless reflection.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Disadvantages include discontinuity, a high about of indexing, linear interpolation of vectors (when calculated in hardware), filtering across texture map boundaries, and possibly the need for multiple textures.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Computer-aided design (CAD) programs use specular highlights as visual cues to convey a sense of surface curvature when rendering 3D objects.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] However, many CAD programs exhibit problems in sampling specular highlights because the specular lighting computations are only performed at the vertices of the mesh used to represent the object, and interpolation is used to estimate lighting across the surface of the object.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Problems occur when the mesh vertices are not dense enough, resulting in insufficient sampling of the specular lighting.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] This in turn results in highlights with brightness proportionate to the distance from mesh vertices, ultimately compromising the visual cues that indicate curvature.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] However, this problem cannot be solved by simply creating a denser mesh, as this can greatly reduce the efficiency of object rendering.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Cube maps provide a fairly straightforward and efficient solution to rendering stable specular highlights.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Multiple specular highlights can be encoded into a cube map texture, which can then be accessed by interpolating across the surface's reflection vector to supply coordinates.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Relative to computing lighting at individual vertices, this method provides cleaner results that more accurately represent curvature.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Another advantage to this method is that it scales well, as additional specular highlights can be encoded into the texture at no increase in the cost of rendering.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] However, this approach is limited in that the light sources must be either distant or infinite lights, although this is usually the case in CAD programs.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Renders using cubemaps can look better in outdoor scenes.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Perhaps the most advanced application of cube mapping is to create pre-rendered panoramic sky images which are then rendered by the graphical engine as faces of a cube at practically infinite distance with the view point located in the center of the cube.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] The perspective projection of the cube faces done by the graphics engine undoes the effects of projecting the environment to create the cube map, so that the observer experiences an illusion of being surrounded by the scene which was used to generate the skybox.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] This technique has found a widespread use in video games since it allows designers to add complex (albeit not explorable) environments to a game at almost no performance cost.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Cube maps can be useful for modelling outdoor illumination accurately.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Simply modelling sunlight as a single infinite light oversimplifies outdoor illumination and results in unrealistic lighting.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Although plenty of light does come from the sun, the scattering of rays in the atmosphere causes the whole sky to act as a light source (often referred to as skylight illumination).
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] However, by using a cube map, the diffuse contribution from skylight illumination can be captured.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Unlike environment maps where the reflection vector is used, this method accesses the cube map based on the surface normal vector to provide a fast approximation of the diffuse illumination from the skylight.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] The one downside to this method is that computing cube maps to properly represent a skylight is very complex; one recent process is computing the spherical harmonic basis that best represents the low frequency diffuse illumination from the cube map.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] However, a considerable amount of research has been done to effectively model skylight illumination.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Basic environment mapping uses a static cube map – although the object can be moved and distorted, the reflected environment stays consistent.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] However, a cube map texture can be consistently updated to represent a dynamically changing environment (for example, trees swaying in the wind).
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] A simple yet costly way to generate dynamic reflections involves building the cube maps at runtime for every frame.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Although this is far less efficient than static mapping because of additional rendering steps, it can still be performed at interactive rates.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] However, this technique does not scale well when multiple reflective objects are present.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] A unique dynamic environment map is usually required for each reflective object.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Also, further complications are added if reflective objects can reflect each other – dynamic cube maps can be recursively generated, approximating the effects normally generated using raytracing.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] An algorithm for global illumination computation at interactive rates using a cube map data structure, was presented at ICCVG 2002.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] Another application which found widespread use in video games is projective texture mapping.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] It relies on cube maps to project images of an environment onto the surrounding scene; for example, a point light source is tied to a cube map which is a panoramic image shot from inside a lantern cage or a window frame through which the light is filtering.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] This enables a game developer to achieve realistic lighting without having to complicate the scene geometry or resort to expensive real-time shadow volume computations.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] A cube texture indexes six texture maps from 0 to 5 in order: positive X, negative X, positive Y, negative Y, positive Z, negative Z.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] The images are stored with the origin at the lower left of the image.
[src:image-based-lighting/cube-map] The positive X and Y faces must reverse the Z coordinate and the negative Z face must negate the X coordinate.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] In computer graphics, **reflection mapping** or **environment mapping** is an efficient image-based lighting technique for approximating the appearance of a reflective surface by means of a precomputed texture.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] The texture is used to store the image of the distant environment surrounding the rendered object.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Several ways of storing the surrounding environment have been employed.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] The first technique was sphere mapping, in which a single texture contains the image of the surroundings as reflected on a spherical mirror.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] It has been almost entirely surpassed by cube mapping, in which the environment is projected onto the six faces of a cube and stored as six square textures or unfolded into six square regions of a single texture.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Other projections that have some superior mathematical or computational properties include the paraboloid mapping, the pyramid mapping, the octahedron mapping, and the HEALPix mapping.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Reflection mapping is one of several approaches to reflection rendering, alongside e.g. screen space reflections or ray tracing which computes the exact reflection by tracing a ray of light and following its optical path.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] The reflection color used in the shading computation at a pixel is determined by calculating the reflection vector at the point on the object and mapping it to the texel in the environment map.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] However, in most circumstances a mapped reflection is only an approximation of the real reflection.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] The object being shaded is convex, such that it contains no self-interreflections.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] When this is not the case the object does not appear in the reflection; only the environment does.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Environment mapping is generally the fastest method of rendering a reflective surface.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] To further increase the speed of rendering, the renderer may calculate the position of the reflected ray at each vertex.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Then, the position is interpolated across polygons to which the vertex is attached.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] This eliminates the need for recalculating every pixel's reflection direction.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] If normal mapping is used, each polygon has many face normals (the direction a given point on a polygon is facing), which can be used in tandem with an environment map to produce a more realistic reflection.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] In this case, the angle of reflection at a given point on a polygon will take the normal map into consideration.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] This technique is used to make an otherwise flat surface appear textured, for example corrugated metal, or brushed aluminium.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Sphere mapping represents the sphere of incident illumination as though it were seen in the reflection of a reflective sphere through an orthographic camera.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] The texture image can be created by approximating this ideal setup, or using a fisheye lens or via prerendering a scene with a spherical mapping.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] The spherical mapping suffers from limitations that detract from the realism of resulting renderings.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] The spherical mapping also wastes pixels that are in the square but not in the sphere.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] The artifacts of the spherical mapping are so severe that it is effective only for viewpoints near that of the virtual orthographic camera.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Cube mapping and other polyhedron mappings address the severe distortion of sphere maps.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] If cube maps are made and filtered correctly, they have no visible seams, and can be used independent of the viewpoint of the often-virtual camera acquiring the map.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Cube and other polyhedron maps have since superseded sphere maps in most computer graphics applications, with the exception of acquiring image-based lighting.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Image-based lighting can be done with parallax-corrected cube maps.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Generally, cube mapping uses the same skybox that is used in outdoor renderings.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Cube-mapped reflection is done by determining the vector that the object is being viewed at.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] This *camera ray* is reflected about the surface normal of where the camera vector intersects the object.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] This results in the *reflected ray* which is then passed to the cube map to get the texel which provides the radiance value used in the lighting calculation.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] This creates the effect that the object is reflective.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] HEALPix environment mapping is similar to the other polyhedron mappings, but can be hierarchical, thus providing a unified framework for generating polyhedra that better approximate the sphere.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] This allows lower distortion at the cost of increased computation.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] In 1974, Edwin Catmull created an algorithm for "rendering images of bivariate surface patches" which worked directly with their mathematical definition.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Gene Miller experimented with spherical environment mapping in 1982 at MAGI.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Wolfgang Heidrich introduced Paraboloid Mapping in 1998.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Emil Praun introduced Octahedron Mapping in 2003.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Mauro Steigleder introduced Pyramid Mapping in 2005.
[src:image-based-lighting/environment-mapping] Tien-Tsin Wong, et al. introduced the existing HEALPix mapping for rendering in 2006.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Graphics processor company Nvidia summarizes the motivation for HDRR in three points: bright things can be really bright, dark things can be really dark, and details can be seen in both.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The use of high-dynamic-range imaging (HDRI) in computer graphics was introduced by Greg Ward in 1985 with his open-source Radiance rendering and *lighting simulation* software which created the first file format to retain a high-dynamic-range image.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDRI languished for more than a decade, held back by limited computing power, storage, and capture methods.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Not until recently has the technology to put HDRI into practical use been developed.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1990, Eihachiro Nakame and associates presented a lighting model for driving simulators that highlighted the need for high-dynamic-range processing in realistic simulations.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1995, Greg Spencer presented *Physically-based glow visual effects for digital images* at SIGGRAPH, providing a quantitative model for flare and blooming in the human eye.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1997, Paul Debevec presented *Recovering high dynamic range radiance maps from photographs* at SIGGRAPH, and the following year presented *Rendering synthetic objects into real scenes*.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] These two papers laid the framework for creating HDR *light probes* of a location, and then using this probe to light a rendered scene.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDRI and HDRL (high-dynamic-range image-based lighting) have, ever since, been used in many situations in 3D scenes in which inserting a 3D object into a real environment requires the light probe data to provide realistic lighting solutions.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In gaming applications, *Riven: The Sequel to Myst* in 1997 used an HDRI postprocessing shader directly based on Spencer's paper.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] After E3 2003, Valve released a demo movie of their Source engine rendering a cityscape in a high dynamic range.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The term was not commonly used again until E3 2004, where it gained much more attention when Epic Games showcased Unreal Engine 3 and Valve announced *Half-Life 2: Lost Coast* in 2005, coupled with open-source engines such as OGRE 3D and open-source games like *Nexuiz*.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] By the 2010s, HDR displays first became available.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] With higher contrast ratios, HDRR can reduce or eliminate tone mapping, resulting in an even more realistic image.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] One of the primary advantages of HDR rendering is that details in a scene with a large contrast ratio are preserved.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Without HDRR, areas that are too dark are clipped to black and areas that are too bright are clipped to white.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] These are represented by the hardware as a floating point value of 0.0 and 1.0 for pure black and pure white, respectively.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Another aspect of HDR rendering is the addition of perceptual cues which increase apparent brightness.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDR rendering also affects how light is preserved in optical phenomena such as reflections and refractions, as well as transparent materials such as glass.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In LDR rendering, very bright light sources in a scene (such as the sun) are capped at 1.0.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] When this light is reflected the result must then be less than or equal to 1.0.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, in HDR rendering, very bright light sources can exceed the 1.0 brightness to simulate their actual values.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This allows reflections off surfaces to maintain realistic brightness for bright light sources.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The human eye can perceive scenes with a very high dynamic contrast ratio, around 1,000,000:1.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Adaptation is achieved in part through adjustments of the iris and slow chemical changes, which take some time (e.g. the delay in being able to see when switching from bright lighting to pitch darkness).
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] At any given time, the eye's static range is smaller, around 10,000:1.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, this is still higher than the static range of most display technology.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Although many manufacturers claim very high numbers, plasma displays, liquid-crystal displays, and CRT displays can deliver only a fraction of the contrast ratio found in the real world, and these are usually measured under ideal conditions.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The simultaneous contrast of real content under normal viewing conditions is significantly lower.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Some increase in dynamic range in LCD monitors can be achieved by automatically reducing the backlight for dark scenes.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] For example, LG calls this technology "Digital Fine Contrast"; Samsung describes it as "dynamic contrast ratio".
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Another technique is to have an array of brighter and darker LED backlights, for example with systems developed by BrightSide Technologies.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] OLED displays have better dynamic range capabilities than LCDs, similar to plasma but with lower power consumption.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] 709 defines the color space for HDTV, and Rec.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] 2020 defines a larger but still incomplete color space for ultra-high-definition television.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Since the 2010s, OLED and other HDR display technologies have reduced or eliminated the need for tone mapping HDRR to standard dynamic range.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Light blooming is the result of scattering in the human lens, which human brain interprets as a bright spot in a scene.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] For example, a bright light in the background will appear to bleed over onto objects in the foreground.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This can be used to create an illusion to make the bright spot appear to be brighter than it really is.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Flare is the diffraction of light in the human lens, resulting in "rays" of light emanating from small light sources, and can also result in some chromatic effects.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It is most visible on point light sources because of their small visual angle.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Typical display devices cannot display light as bright as the Sun, and ambient room lighting prevents them from displaying true black.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Thus, HDR rendering systems have to map the full dynamic range of what the eye would see in the rendered situation onto the capabilities of the device.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This tone mapping is done relative to what the virtual scene camera sees, combined with several full screen effects, e.g. to simulate dust in the air which is lit by direct sunlight in a dark cavern, or the scattering in the eye.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Tone mapping and blooming shaders can be used together to help simulate these effects.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Tone mapping, in the context of graphics rendering, is a technique used to map colors from high dynamic range (in which lighting calculations are performed) to a lower dynamic range that matches the capabilities of the desired display device.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Typically, the mapping is non-linear – it preserves enough range for dark colors and gradually limits the dynamic range for bright colors.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This technique often produces visually appealing images with good overall detail and contrast.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Various tone mapping operators exist, ranging from simple real-time methods used in computer games to more sophisticated techniques that attempt to imitate the perceptual response of the human visual system.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDR displays with higher dynamic range capabilities can reduce or eliminate the tone mapping required after HDRR, resulting in an even more realistic image.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Currently HDRR has been prevalent in games, primarily for PCs but was previously prevalent in Microsoft's Xbox 360and Sony's PlayStation 3.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It has also been simulated on the PlayStation 2, GameCube, Xbox and Amiga systems.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Sproing Interactive Media had announced that their Athena game engine for the Wii will support HDRR, which added the Wii to the list of systems that support it.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In desktop publishing and gaming, color values are often processed several times over.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] As this includes multiplication and division (which can accumulate rounding errors), it is useful to have the extended accuracy and range of 16-bit integer or 16-bit floating point formats.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This is useful irrespective of the aforementioned limitations in some hardware.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Complex shader effects began their days with the release of Shader Model 1.0 with DirectX 8.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 1.0 illuminated 3D worlds with what is called standard lighting.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Lighting calculations were integer based, which didn't offer as much accuracy because the real world is not confined to whole numbers.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On December 24, 2002, Microsoft released a new version of DirectX.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] DirectX 9.0 introduced Shader Model 2.0, which offered one of the necessary components to enable rendering of high-dynamic-range images: lighting precision was not limited to just 8-bits.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Although 8-bits was the minimum in applications, programmers could choose up to a maximum of 24 bits for lighting precision.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, all calculations were still integer-based.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] One of the first graphics cards to support DirectX 9.0 natively was ATI's Radeon 9700, though the effect wasn't programmed into games for years afterwards.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On August 23, 2003, Microsoft updated DirectX to DirectX 9.0b, which enabled the Pixel Shader 2.x (Extended) profile for ATI's Radeon X series and NVIDIA's GeForce FX series of graphics processing units.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On August 9, 2004, Microsoft updated DirectX once more to DirectX 9.0c.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This also exposed the Shader Model 3.0 profile for High-Level Shader Language (HLSL).
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 3.0's lighting precision has a minimum of 32 bits as opposed to 2.0's 8-bit minimum.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Also all lighting-precision calculations are now floating-point based.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] NVIDIA states that contrast ratios using Shader Model 3.0 can be as high as 65535:1 using 32-bit lighting precision.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] At first, HDRR was only possible on video cards capable of Shader-Model-3.0 effects, but software developers soon added compatibility for Shader Model 2.0.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] As a side note, when referred to as Shader Model 3.0 HDR, HDRR is really done by FP16 blending.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] FP16 blending is not part of Shader Model 3.0, but is supported mostly by cards also capable of Shader Model 3.0 (exceptions include the GeForce 6200 series).
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] FP16 blending can be used as a faster way to render HDR in video games.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 4.0 is a feature of DirectX 10, which was released with Windows Vista.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 4.0 allows 128-bit HDR rendering, as opposed to 64-bit HDR in Shader Model 3.0 (although this is theoretically possible under Shader Model 3.0).
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 5.0 is a feature of DirectX 11.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It allows 6:1 compression of HDR textures without noticeable loss, which is prevalent in previous versions of DirectX HDR texture compression techniques.
[src:image-based-lighting/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It is possible to develop HDRR through GLSL shader starting from OpenGL 1.4 onwards.
[src:image-based-lighting/image-based-lighting] Image-based lighting often uses high-dynamic-range imaging for greater realism, though this is not universal.
[src:image-based-lighting/image-based-lighting] Motion picture production makes use of image-based lighting, and it can be seen in movies like *Monsters University*, *The Great Gatsby*, and *Iron Man 2*.
[src:image-based-lighting/image-based-lighting] One reference capture technique, sometimes referred to as "wickmania" by camera technicians and VFX supervisors, involves shooting footage of two small spheres (one matte, one of a light-reflective material) on a physical set.
[src:image-based-lighting/image-based-lighting] This is used when the IBL will be later applied to an animated object or character that interacts with live objects or characters under the same lighting conditions.
[src:image-based-lighting/image-based-lighting] Image-based lighting is also used in some video games as video game consoles and personal computers start to have the computational resources to render scenes in real time using this technique.
[src:image-based-lighting/image-based-lighting] Image-based lighting is also a built-in feature of the Crytek CryEngine video game engine.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] In radiometry, **radiance** is the radiant flux emitted, reflected, transmitted or received by a given surface, per unit solid angle per unit projected area.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Radiance is used to characterize diffuse emission and reflection of electromagnetic radiation, and to quantify emission of neutrinos and other particles.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] The SI unit of radiance is the watt per steradian per square metre (W·sr−1·m−2).
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] It is a *directional* quantity: the radiance of a surface depends on the direction from which it is being observed.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] The related quantity spectral radiance is the radiance of a surface per unit frequency or wavelength, depending on whether the spectrum is taken as a function of frequency or of wavelength.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Historically, radiance was called "intensity" and spectral radiance was called "specific intensity".
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Many fields still use this nomenclature.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] It is especially dominant in heat transfer, astrophysics and astronomy.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] "Intensity" has many other meanings in physics, with the most common being power per unit area (so the radiance is the intensity per solid angle in this case).
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Radiance is useful because it indicates how much of the power emitted, reflected, transmitted, or received by a surface will be received by an optical system looking at that surface from a specified angle of view.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] In this case, the solid angle of interest is the solid angle subtended by the optical system's entrance pupil.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Since the eye is an optical system, radiance and its cousin luminance are good indicators of how bright an object will appear.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] For this reason, radiance and luminance are both sometimes called "brightness".
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] This usage is now discouraged (see the article Brightness for a discussion).
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] The nonstandard usage of "brightness" for "radiance" persists in some fields, notably laser physics.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] The radiance divided by the index of refraction squared is invariant in geometric optics.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] This means that for an ideal optical system in air, the radiance at the output is the same as the input radiance.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] This is sometimes called *conservation of radiance*.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] For real, passive, optical systems, the output radiance is *at most* equal to the input, unless the index of refraction changes.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] As an example, if you form a demagnified image with a lens, the optical power is concentrated into a smaller area, so the irradiance is higher at the image.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] The light at the image plane, however, fills a larger solid angle so the radiance comes out to be the same assuming there is no loss at the lens.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Spectral radiance expresses radiance as a function of frequency or wavelength.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Radiance is the integral of the spectral radiance over all frequencies or wavelengths.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] For radiation emitted by the surface of an ideal black body at a given temperature, spectral radiance is governed by Planck's law, while the integral of its radiance, over the hemisphere into which its surface radiates, is given by the Stefan–Boltzmann law.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Its surface is Lambertian, so that its radiance is uniform with respect to angle of view, and is simply the Stefan–Boltzmann integral divided by π.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] This factor is obtained from the solid angle 2π steradians of a hemisphere decreased by integration over the cosine of the zenith angle.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] In general *L*e,Ω is a function of viewing direction, depending on *θ* through cos *θ* and azimuth angle through ∂Φe/∂Ω.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] For the special case of a Lambertian surface, ∂2Φe/(∂Ω ∂*A*) is proportional to cos *θ*, and *L*e,Ω is isotropic (independent of viewing direction).
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] When calculating the radiance emitted by a source, *A* refers to an area on the surface of the source, and Ω to the solid angle into which the light is emitted.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] When calculating radiance received by a detector, *A* refers to an area on the surface of the detector and Ω to the solid angle subtended by the source as viewed from that detector.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] When radiance is conserved, as discussed above, the radiance emitted by a source is the same as that received by a detector observing it.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] As the light travels through an ideal optical system, both the étendue and the radiant flux are conserved.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] In real systems, the étendue may increase (for example due to scattering) or the radiant flux may decrease (for example due to absorption) and, therefore, basic radiance may decrease.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] However, étendue may not decrease and radiant flux may not increase and, therefore, basic radiance may not increase.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Alternative symbols sometimes seen: W or E for radiant energy, P or F for radiant flux, I for irradiance, W for radiant exitance.
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Spectral quantities given per unit wavelength are denoted with suffix "*λ*".
[src:image-based-lighting/radiance] Directional quantities are denoted with suffix "Ω".
